```yaml
verdict: defend
probe_engaged: yes
new_grade: null
rationale: |
  The GreyNoise 20-month continuous mass-SSH-scanning record for 203.0.113.45 is the
  specific piece of evidence that holds the grade against this counterfactual. A targeted
  attacker borrowing this IP to masquerade as background noise would have had to establish
  or acquire 20 months of scanner-consistent behavioral history before the incident — a
  cost that falsifies the "deliberately selected wordlist + paced requests" evasion scenario
  as a simple in-session choice. The probe is epistemically valid when only session-level
  authentication logs are available, but the ANALYZE block cited IP-level reputation data
  as independent corroboration extending the evidence base beyond the authentication pattern
  alone. Even granting the adversary-mimic scenario, the disposition (true_positive,
  external-bruteforce) is unchanged — the probe contests mechanism label, not maliciousness,
  and the ++ grade reflects the observable mechanism matching all pre-committed predictions
  from a direct SIEM query, not a claim that sophisticated mimicry is impossible.
